<subSubSection id="9300128AA00F138EAAD861A2EB04505E" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph id="53D13EDF5BDC10AA3971E931185A525F" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F34973FFA059298DBAEFDD2E2394B4BF" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">
A very rare species in the Greek territory. There is only one previously confirmed record from Mt. Belles (also known as Mt. Kerkini) by 
<bibRefCitation id="39ECB32CC8B7A48E46B0E97A53D73727" author="Strid, A." journalOrPublisher="Willdenowia, 42 (2): 287 - 295" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" refId="B7669412" refString="Strid, A., 2012. Med-Checklist Notulae 31. Willdenowia, 42 (2): 287-295" title="Med-Checklist Notulae 31" year="2012">Strid (2012)</bibRefCitation>
, while a historical collection on Mt. Olimbos by Pichler in 1874 may need confirmation (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="36C80C26182832CFF153DAD99F404DE8" captionStart="Figure 17" captionStartId="F7677669" captionText="Figure 17. Distribution map of Convolvulus suendermannii, Lomelosia rhodopensis, Drymocallis rupestris and Saxifraga pedemontana subsp. cymosa in Greece." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e81817.figure17" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/656581" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">17</figureCitation>
). This new locality from the Rodopi Mountain range comes not as a surprise, as 
<taxonomicName id="E387669225DE550954817B69D7E076EE" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Drymocallis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Drymocallis rupestris" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="rupestris">
<emphasis id="B6C25D269A148CCDF6CE1BA192D9FF34" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">Drymocallis rupestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has been recorded from the Bulgarian part of the same mountain (
<bibRefCitation id="284EEAEE33239F9C54A61AEC5E5FF61E" author="Sojak, J." journalOrPublisher="Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, Serie" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" pagination="319 - 328" refId="B7669347" refString="Sojak, J., 2011. Synopsis of Drymocallis Fourr. ex Rydb. (Rosaceae - Potentilleae) in the Old World. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, Serie B 112: 319 - 328" title="Synopsis of Drymocallis Fourr. ex Rydb. (Rosaceae - Potentilleae) in the Old World" volume="B 112" year="2011">
<normalizedToken id="40CC509DCF53DDE95F34E7F339AA85E2" originalValue="Soják">Sojak</normalizedToken>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
). Our collected plants (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="25423D26FD89C26334299C0AAAAE1394" captionStart="Figure 21" captionStartId="F7677692" captionText="Figure 21. Drymocallis rupestris from Mt Rodopi (photo: P. Doumas)." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.10.e81817.figure21" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/640571" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">21</figureCitation>
) have short stems 10-16 cm high (in contrast to the 15-60 cm high stems of the central European collections) and a rather variable indumentum on leaf petioles and pedicels consisting of mostly patent hairs that become obliquely-patent below the flowers. Morphologically, they may represent transition forms between subsp. 
<taxonomicName id="AE8D572C59C5C546BE2566F15EB0BECD" authority="rupestris" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Drymocallis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Drymocallis rupestris subsp. rupestris" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="rupestris" subSpecies="rupestris">Drymocallis rupestris rupestris</taxonomicName>
and subsp. 
<taxonomicName id="CC6ADEA525EFEB79FF4B55BB04958A36" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Drymocallis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Drymocallis rupestris subsp. banatica" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="rupestris" subSpecies="banatica">Drymocallis rupestris banatica</taxonomicName>
(Th. Wolf) 
<normalizedToken id="DB21479F0BD7952D3AEF26A3B71BA40B" originalValue="Soják">Sojak</normalizedToken>
. The Rodopi plants grow on rocky slopes, in openings of pine forest and, because of their small size, resemble the Bulgarian dwarf specimens (5-10 cm tall) of subsp. 
<taxonomicName id="FF08EDE04E27F45630ED4D72256BC345" authority="rupestris" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Drymocallis" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Drymocallis rupestris subsp. rupestris" order="Rosales" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="subSpecies" species="rupestris" subSpecies="rupestris">Drymocallis rupestris rupestris</taxonomicName>
discussed by 
<bibRefCitation id="68442E927329530B27131E7BB3DF7797" author="Sojak, J." journalOrPublisher="Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, Serie" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" pagination="319 - 328" refId="B7669347" refString="Sojak, J., 2011. Synopsis of Drymocallis Fourr. ex Rydb. (Rosaceae - Potentilleae) in the Old World. Annalen des Naturhistorischen Museums in Wien, Serie B 112: 319 - 328" title="Synopsis of Drymocallis Fourr. ex Rydb. (Rosaceae - Potentilleae) in the Old World" volume="B 112" year="2011">
<normalizedToken id="FA26596950FFF3420F367F74DA35E27A" originalValue="Soják">Sojak</normalizedToken>
(2011)
</bibRefCitation>
. Presumably, the adaptation to rocky substrates and a more xeric environment are responsible for the dwarf habit of our 
<taxonomicName id="1603EEC067E8955C8B2320051FDDFD9A" genus="D." lsidName="D. rupestris" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="rupestris">
<emphasis id="BAA89F4BF4C17486C3A9A6F365A8D670" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">D. rupestris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
samples, but also of the related 
<taxonomicName id="589A23D2128E027C084E254428EED5FA" genus="D." lsidName="D. halacsyana" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817" rank="species" species="halacsyana">
<emphasis id="DCE01405B8F9A96ED1460C30CA7FE6CC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="81817">D. halacsyana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Degen) Kurtto &amp; Strid found on Mt. Saos of Samothraki Island, ca. 110 km to the south-east.
</paragraph>
